occurrences.line_text: And as ye soft and tender are by kynde,
So be ye soft and tender eeke in mynde;
Thought sure haue pownded him to powder soft,
For loue in soft delight thereon to rest;
Sprinckle her heart, and haughtie courage soften,
My softened heart so sorely doth constraine,
So slyding softly forth, she turnd as to her ease.
Which softly ecchoed from the neighbour wood;
And softly can embalme on euery side.
Did softly swim away, ne euer stampe,
And handle softly, till they can be healed:
Whom hauing softly disarayd of armes,
Her daintie limbes full softly down did lay:
With his faire garment: then gan softly feele
Vplifted light, and softly did vphold:
And twixt the perles and rubins softly brake
And fast beside, there trickled softly downe
On a sweet bed of lillies softly layd,
In her loose lap, it softly to sustaine,
Which Guyons senses softly tickeled,
She softly felt, if any member mooued,
And by her side her selfe she softly layd,
Thereat she sighing softly, had no powre
And softly sunck into her molten hart;
She softly felt, and rubbed busily,
Therewith th'Enchaunter softly gan to smyle
Then sighing softly sore, and inly deepe,
Whiles on his broad round backe they softly slid
And let their temed fishes softly swim
They softly gan to search his griesly wound:
They softly wipt away the gelly blood
Vpon great Neptunes necke they softly swim,
Few trickling teares she softly forth let fall,
Softly at last he gan his mother aske,
And with his frory lips full softly kist,
Fell softly forth, as of his owne accord,
Shee with her rod did softly smite the raile,
Which drawing softly forth out of the darke,
To lend an eare, and softly to relent.
Which she long listning, softly askt againe
Which softly stild, and kissing them atweene,
And with few drops thereof did softly dew
So forth they yode, and forward softly paced,
And next to him the Nene downe softly slid;
To whom God Neptune softly smyling, thus;
A Knight, that softly paced on the plaine,
And softly royne, when saluage choler gan redound.
Ryding a softly pace with portance sad,
And softly whispering him, entyrely prayd,
His siluer waues did softly tumble downe,
Th'abandond spoyle, he softly it vnbound;
She long so held, and softly weeping sayd;
And soild with dust of the long dried way;
Lying on ground, all soild with bloud and mire:
From loathed soile he can him lightly reare,
Saue in that soile, where all good things did grow,
The sacred soile, where all our perils grow;
My natiue soile haue left, my dayes to spend
In the coole soile, after long thirstinesse,
And water all the English soile throughout;
Besides them both, vpon the soiled gras
Themselues of soiled armes, and to prepare
To make there lenger soiourne and abode;
That he there soiourned his wounds to heale;
There Atin found Cymochles soiourning,
T'abate all spasme, and soke the swelling bruze,
To take the solace of the open aire,
Vnkindnesse past, they gan of solace treat,
No solace could her Paramour intreat,
Making sweet solace to her selfe alone;
Themselues did solace each one with his Dame,
Where goodly solace was vnto them made,
Did greatly solace his engrieued mind.
To rest him selfe, and solace in soft pleasure
Delightfull bowres, to solace louers trew;
This day as I in solace sate hereby
As if him selfe to solace he were faine.
To solace with his Lady in delight:
Each gan his fellow solace and embrace,
So hauing solaced themselues a space
Was the faire Witch her selfe now solacing,
Well solast in that Souldans late delight,
And vnto hell him selfe for money sold;
And sold thy selfe to serue Duessa vilde,
Like euer saw, but they from hence were sold;
But were your will, her sold to entertaine,
That hath himselfe vnto such seruice sold,
That she her loue and hart hath wholy sold
That vnto Venus seruices was sold.
To whom the right hereof it selfe hath sold;
Which sought vnrighteousnesse, and iustice sold,
Fie on the pelfe, for which good name is sold,
Or sold againe. Now when faire Pastorell
Be sold, and mongst them shared equally.
And sold for most aduantage not to be forstalled.
Bad them be still, his loue should not be sold:
Should with the rest be sold before him theare,
Or how faire Pastorell should haue bene sold
The builder Oake, sole king of forrests all,
Borne the sole daughter of an Emperour,
As seeming plast in sole felicity:
By his sole manhood and atchieuement stout
Well knowing her to be his deaths sole instrument.
And kist the ground on which her sole did tread,
For whose sole libertie I loue and life did stake.
To none, but to the seas sole Soueraine.
Euen from the sole of his foundation,
Fled fast into the towne, and her sole victor left.
To Gods sole grace, whom she did oft implore,
Her selfe sole left, a second spoyle to bee
But of his cheere did seeme too solemne sad;
And in the wine a solemne oth they bynd
There raignd a solemne silence ouer all,
Then all the people, as in solemne feast,
At last his solemne silence thus he brake,
And solemne feast proclaimd throughout the land,
An yearely solemne feast she wontes to make
He then with solemne oath and plighted hand
Still solemne sad, or still disdainfull coy,
As it some Gyeld or solemne Temple weare:
But somwhat sad, and solemne eke in sight,
A solemne Meane vnto them measured,
Sad, solemne, sowre, and full of fancies fraile
And solemne silence ouer all that place:
A solemne feast, with publike turneying,
It fortun'd then, a solemne feast was there
And ioy likewise this solemne day to see?
Iustice sate high ador'd with solemne feasts,
And solemne feasts and giusts ordain'd therefore.
Were present at this great solemnity:
Whose vertues through the wyde world soone were solemniz'd.
Should be solemniz'd: for if time he had,

And made great feast to solemnize that day;

Yet ceasest not thy wearie soles to lead,
Forsaken, wofull, solitarie mayd
So choosing solitarie to abide,

And finding there fit solitary place
In solitary silence far from wight,
And to her chamber went like solitary cell.
Seeing her selfe all soly succourlesse,
Seemed in heart some hidden care she had,
Enforst to seeke some couert nigh at hand,
Till that some end they finde or in or out,
